post_cb({"12411370": {"CommentCount": "10", "ViewCount": "808", "PostTypeId": "1", "LastEditorUserId": "636019", "CreationDate": "2012-09-13T17:07:25.207", "LastActivityDate": "2012-09-13T20:46:16.903", "Title": "Performance guarantees for now() call of standard chrono clocks?", "LastEditDate": "2012-09-13T20:46:16.903", "Id": "12411370", "Score": "2", "Body": "<p>Are there any performance guarantees in the standard required for the implement of the now() static functions of each clock in std::chrono?</p>\n<p>In n3337 I read that ( 20.11.3 Clock requirements [time.clock.req] ):</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_12411370_12411370_0\">3 [ Note: The relative di\ufb00erence in durations between those reported\n  by a given clock and the SI de\ufb01nition is a measure of the quality of\n  implementation. \u2014 end note ]</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Does this mean that it is totally implementation-dependent? Or did I miss something?</p>\n", "Tags": "<c++><performance><c++11><std><chrono>", "OwnerUserId": "2368", "AnswerCount": "1"}, "12411477": {"ParentId": "12411370", "CommentCount": "0", "Body": "<p>The speed, accuracy, resolution, etc., of the standard clocks are all totally implementation dependent. There are no requirements for any of these aspects of the clocks' performance.</p>\n<p>I imagine most any implementation will offer pretty much the best speed and accuracy available from the hardware. On the other hand resolution seems to vary between implementations, with some providing nanoseconds and others providing considerably lower resolution.</p>\n", "OwnerUserId": "365496", "PostTypeId": "2", "Id": "12411477", "Score": "4", "CreationDate": "2012-09-13T17:15:01.097", "LastActivityDate": "2012-09-13T17:15:01.097"}, "bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_12411370_12411370_0": {"section_id": 4740, "quality": 0.625, "length": 10}}, "n3337": {"so_12411370_12411370_0": {"section_id": 4547, "quality": 0.625, "length": 10}}, "n4659": {"so_12411370_12411370_0": {"section_id": 6151, "quality": 0.625, "length": 10}}}});